WEBVTT

00:05.339 --> 00:06.640
[Catherine] <i>Previously</i>
<i>on</i> The Spanish Princess...

00:06.674 --> 00:08.542
The time to strike is now.

00:08.576 --> 00:10.311
<i>The queen carries my son,</i>

00:10.344 --> 00:13.214
as I shall carry the banner
of England into France.

00:13.247 --> 00:14.548
-[cheering]
-[Meg] <i>Invade?</i>

00:14.582 --> 00:17.084
You can't possibly.
We have a treaty with England.

00:17.118 --> 00:19.286
Scotland has an even
older one with France.

00:19.320 --> 00:21.021
And you declare war on my family?

00:21.055 --> 00:24.024
[Catherine] England is a land of women
and children in our army's absence.

00:24.058 --> 00:25.226
Someone must defend them.

00:25.259 --> 00:27.228
Advance!

00:27.261 --> 00:30.097
-[chaotic shouting]
-[blade plunges]

00:30.131 --> 00:32.066
-[Lina groaning]
-The baby comes.

00:32.099 --> 00:36.270
You have taken from me
the father of my two sons.

00:36.303 --> 00:39.407
-[Catherine] Your sister Meg is grieving.
-My sister Meg reigns over Scotland.

00:39.440 --> 00:40.508
She should be glad.

00:40.541 --> 00:42.710
She and her sons will keep
their peace with us.

00:42.743 --> 00:44.812
If you need to talk to somebody, I'm here.

00:45.045 --> 00:46.747
He is a healthy baby boy,

00:46.781 --> 00:48.215
<i>and he has a twin brother.</i>

00:48.249 --> 00:50.451
[Wolsey] <i>Nothing is more important</i>
<i>than the king's heir.</i>

00:50.484 --> 00:51.719
-[groans]
-[Henry] Catherine!

00:51.752 --> 00:53.320
Fetch a nurse!

00:53.354 --> 00:56.357
[lively orchestral music]

00:56.390 --> 00:59.360
♪ ♪

01:44.171 --> 01:47.141
[choral music]

01:47.174 --> 01:49.877
♪ ♪

02:03.624 --> 02:05.192
[sobbing]

02:05.226 --> 02:06.494
[Henry] <i>It's a boy.</i>

02:06.527 --> 02:09.497
[choral music continues]

02:09.530 --> 02:12.533
♪ ♪

02:24.778 --> 02:27.748
[gentle music]

02:27.781 --> 02:30.784
♪ ♪

02:32.786 --> 02:35.523
[indistinct chatter]

02:35.556 --> 02:37.725
Catherine.

02:37.758 --> 02:39.226
I know.

02:41.729 --> 02:44.698
[Brandon]
Even the Hanging Gardens of Babylon

02:44.732 --> 02:47.535
cannot compare
to one English orchard in summer.

02:47.568 --> 02:49.370
[Stafford]
I concede the point, Brandon.

02:49.403 --> 02:52.940
The only view I remember in France
was the great sea of horses' asses

02:53.173 --> 02:55.175
as the French army retreated.

02:55.209 --> 02:56.710
[Henry]
At the first flash of English metal!

02:56.744 --> 02:58.379
His Grace led a brilliant attack.

02:58.412 --> 02:59.813
[Catherine]
I'll raise a toast to it.

02:59.847 --> 03:01.715
The queen, too? She had a victory?

03:01.749 --> 03:03.584
[pounding on table]

03:03.617 --> 03:05.452
No, the queen had a loss.

03:08.556 --> 03:09.957
Indeed.

03:10.190 --> 03:12.960
But now we must look to the future.

03:13.193 --> 03:16.230
We must remember that peace
is much less costly

03:16.263 --> 03:17.665
to the royal purse than war.

03:17.698 --> 03:20.234
The king has silenced France, Wolsey.

03:20.768 --> 03:21.769
He has won the war.

03:21.802 --> 03:23.370
[Wolsey]
Yes, he has.

03:23.404 --> 03:27.241
But now we must consider
who our European allies are.

03:27.274 --> 03:30.277
[Catherine] We are very clear
who our allies are, chaplain.

03:31.845 --> 03:34.915
Despite our grievances with Ferdinand,
Spain remains our ally.

03:34.949 --> 03:36.984
Your Grace, your father, Ferdinand,

03:37.217 --> 03:40.621
cannot be rewarded for his treachery.

03:40.654 --> 03:42.323
That would make the king look weak.

03:42.356 --> 03:44.625
[Catherine]
As would making terms with France.

03:44.658 --> 03:48.362
Our people have been taxed to the hilt
to fund the war with them.

03:48.395 --> 03:49.797
We cannot make light of their sacrifice.

03:49.830 --> 03:53.434
[Wolsey] Nor maintain hostility
for sentimental reasons.

03:53.467 --> 03:55.769
We should dissolve
Princess Mary's engagement

03:55.803 --> 03:57.638
to your nephew Charles

03:57.671 --> 04:00.608
and instead match her with King Louis

04:00.641 --> 04:03.577
to make our peace with France.

04:03.611 --> 04:05.846
[laughs]

04:05.879 --> 04:09.283
Did you catch syphilis
from some French whore?

04:09.316 --> 04:11.518
Is this the fever talking?

04:11.552 --> 04:12.753
[scatter laughter]

04:14.655 --> 04:15.789
Wolsey...

04:15.823 --> 04:19.893
I have worked tirelessly to maintain
my nephew's betrothal to Princess Mary.

04:19.927 --> 04:23.530
She's not a piece of meat
to be thrown to French dogs.

04:25.766 --> 04:28.268
[somber music]

04:28.302 --> 04:30.304
[metallic clatter]

04:30.337 --> 04:33.807
♪ ♪

04:33.841 --> 04:36.010
Wolsey's doing this because...

04:37.811 --> 04:40.414
...I have failed to give the king an heir.

04:40.447 --> 04:41.882
You will in time.

04:41.915 --> 04:43.584
The king has always been impatient.

04:43.617 --> 04:45.519
He will not even look at me.

04:46.954 --> 04:48.856
Am I being punished...

04:50.424 --> 04:52.593
...for the claim I made
about my maidenhood?

04:52.626 --> 04:56.430
-Shh, you must never talk about that--
-Is this why my boys are being taken?

04:56.463 --> 04:59.533
Catherine, you must stop this thinking.
It will make you mad.

04:59.566 --> 05:01.769
[Catherine]
God finds me unworthy.

05:01.802 --> 05:05.539
Meanwhile, Wolsey is placing himself
in every part of our lives.

05:06.707 --> 05:09.443
Not in every part, Your Grace.

05:09.476 --> 05:11.578
Your influence over the king
in certain areas

05:11.612 --> 05:13.947
is still solely your domain.

05:16.917 --> 05:18.385
You are right.

05:19.753 --> 05:22.523
I will make him look at me tonight.

05:22.556 --> 05:25.526
[gentle music]

05:25.559 --> 05:28.562
♪ ♪

05:30.764 --> 05:32.066
[Catherine]
Come, Henry.

05:33.701 --> 05:35.402
I am impatient.

05:36.403 --> 05:39.406
♪ ♪

05:39.440 --> 05:42.076
I am impressed at your discretion.

05:46.980 --> 05:50.451
'Tis a great king who does not rise
to provocation.

05:52.419 --> 05:54.555
Who do you think was provoking me?

05:54.588 --> 05:55.689
The chaplain.

05:59.126 --> 06:00.694
Wolsey is right.

06:01.428 --> 06:03.097
Spain betrayed me.

06:04.765 --> 06:06.100
Charles did not.

06:08.102 --> 06:11.839
-I'm exhausted now.
-You will sleep better after we make love.

06:14.041 --> 06:15.909
[Catherine]
Hmm.

06:15.943 --> 06:17.611
See how my hands are trembling?

06:17.644 --> 06:20.514
It has been so long,
it feels like the first time.

06:20.547 --> 06:23.650
You only get one first time, Catherine.

06:23.684 --> 06:26.787
In some rare cases two,
but you pay for it dearly.

06:29.857 --> 06:31.625
It's a joke.

06:33.861 --> 06:34.862
Come.

06:45.405 --> 06:46.974
Catherine, you are unnatural.

06:47.007 --> 06:51.411
What is more natural than a man and woman
married in the eyes of God making love?

06:51.445 --> 06:53.080
I can't be forced.

06:53.113 --> 06:54.982
Then let me help you.

06:58.819 --> 07:01.655
Go sit on the bed over there,
turn your back to me.

07:11.932 --> 07:13.667
Can you lift up your hair?

07:14.668 --> 07:16.003
Show me the nape of your neck.

07:19.840 --> 07:22.075
[breathes deeply]

07:24.545 --> 07:26.814
-Am I disgusting to you?
-Don't look at me!

07:29.049 --> 07:30.584
It has nothing to do with you.

07:30.617 --> 07:33.220
[Catherine]
It has everything to do with me!

07:33.453 --> 07:36.790
I am the only person in the world
who can give you what you want.

07:37.591 --> 07:39.927
So you do whatever you have to do
so you can make love to me.

07:39.960 --> 07:41.728
You put me off now.

07:43.864 --> 07:46.834
[dramatic music]

07:46.867 --> 07:49.837
♪ ♪

08:03.817 --> 08:05.219
Tomorrow, then.

08:08.121 --> 08:09.890
Be ready tomorrow.

08:11.225 --> 08:13.060
You know, Meg wrote to me.

08:13.994 --> 08:16.196
Her two princes thrive.

08:16.230 --> 08:19.233
♪ ♪

08:28.742 --> 08:31.178
[indistinct chatter]

08:31.211 --> 08:33.814
[baby fussing]

08:37.684 --> 08:41.889
Our king is dead, and our son Jamie
is not yet of age to succeed him.

08:41.922 --> 08:43.557
-God rest the king.
-God rest the king.

08:43.590 --> 08:44.992
[Meg] I will be regent
until he is old enough.

08:45.025 --> 08:47.861
The King of England backs me in this.

08:47.895 --> 08:49.563
Your blodig brother?

08:49.596 --> 08:51.565
[Meg] I have his word
that as long as I'm queen,

08:51.598 --> 08:52.699
there will be peace.

08:52.733 --> 08:54.301
[Alexander]
Well, he says that now.

08:54.534 --> 08:57.237
But what's to stop him riding up here,
try to take Edinburgh?

08:57.271 --> 09:01.008
We should throw a wappinshaw
to gather axes, staves, two-handed swords.

09:01.041 --> 09:03.243
We do not need more weapons.
The battle is over.

09:03.277 --> 09:05.746
We at least need cannons
to protect the castle.

09:05.779 --> 09:07.247
If the English take that, then...

09:07.281 --> 09:09.583
[Hume]
Too late. Look who's on the throne.

09:09.616 --> 09:10.918
[baby cries]

09:11.618 --> 09:13.587
James, James, come here, please.

09:13.620 --> 09:17.291
My brother Albany must return from France.

09:17.324 --> 09:18.992
He's next in line to the regency.

09:19.026 --> 09:20.627
-[cheers]
-[Meg] I am regent.

09:20.661 --> 09:22.729
I am queen.

09:22.763 --> 09:26.099
[Hume] Is it not enough that
we could not protect our king?

09:26.133 --> 09:28.335
Is it not shame enough

09:28.568 --> 09:31.171
that we were defeated by those shitey men?

09:31.204 --> 09:33.740
[overlapping agreement]

09:33.774 --> 09:36.109
Well, now we must look to a woman.

09:36.143 --> 09:37.611
An English woman.

09:37.644 --> 09:38.946
The King of England has written to me

09:38.979 --> 09:40.881
that as long as I do not marry,
I will be regent

09:40.914 --> 09:42.182
until Jamie comes of age.

09:42.215 --> 09:44.985
[scattered laughter]

09:45.018 --> 09:46.620
[baby cries]

09:46.653 --> 09:48.322
[Meg]
James, come here now.

09:49.890 --> 09:51.792
Shh. Hush, now.

09:52.359 --> 09:53.360
Thank you.

09:55.262 --> 09:59.132
Hey, look at you,
kissing English arsepiece...

09:59.166 --> 10:01.635
♪ ♪

10:01.668 --> 10:03.136
...just like your father.

10:03.170 --> 10:05.973
♪ ♪

10:13.013 --> 10:14.314
Get off me!

10:14.348 --> 10:15.983
[laughing]

10:16.016 --> 10:17.918
Leave him alone!

10:17.951 --> 10:19.252
Get off him!

10:20.253 --> 10:23.023
I appointed you to my council
to work out how to bring peace,

10:23.056 --> 10:25.826
and look at you, fighting like children.

10:26.360 --> 10:27.761
Get out.

10:27.794 --> 10:29.830
[baby crying]

10:29.863 --> 10:31.665
[Angus grunts]

10:31.698 --> 10:33.667
♪ ♪

10:33.700 --> 10:35.635
Get out!

10:35.669 --> 10:38.238
[baby crying]

10:38.271 --> 10:40.173
[Alexander]
Those children should be silent,

10:40.207 --> 10:41.308
as should their mother.

10:41.341 --> 10:43.210
[baby continues crying]

10:43.243 --> 10:45.846
♪ ♪

10:45.879 --> 10:47.681
My children are not safe
as long as these men

10:47.714 --> 10:49.016
will not be loyal to me.

10:49.049 --> 10:50.817
[continues crying]

10:50.851 --> 10:53.420
[gentle music]

10:53.653 --> 10:56.423
[indistinct chatter]

10:56.656 --> 10:59.659
♪ ♪

11:01.895 --> 11:05.866
-[animal bleats]
-[indistinct chatter continues]

11:05.899 --> 11:08.702
♪ ♪

11:08.735 --> 11:11.738
[baby crying]

11:15.208 --> 11:17.878
Hey. Lady Pole.

11:19.946 --> 11:21.815
Look at those boys.

11:21.848 --> 11:26.019
Ah, eh, Thomas and Barnaby.

11:26.053 --> 11:28.355
Ah, eh, come in.

11:30.023 --> 11:32.459
You are so kind to visit us.

11:32.692 --> 11:34.428
-[Lina] Lady Pole.
-[door closes]

11:34.461 --> 11:36.797
That is for us?

11:36.830 --> 11:40.033
-[sighs] You are kind.
-[crying continues]

11:40.067 --> 11:41.435
May I?

11:43.003 --> 11:44.805
-[baby fussing]
-Shh, shh, shh.

11:44.838 --> 11:47.441
[baby crying]

11:47.474 --> 11:49.276
[Lina]
How is the queen?

11:50.944 --> 11:52.379
She's recovered?

11:54.314 --> 11:55.816
I think so.

11:57.918 --> 11:59.286
Are you well, Lina?

12:01.288 --> 12:02.722
[sighs]

12:07.828 --> 12:11.298
I am not making enough milk
for both of my sons.

12:11.331 --> 12:15.969
And now what little there is is drying up.

12:16.002 --> 12:18.839
Well, you should have
a wet nurse, as I had.

12:18.872 --> 12:23.110
We cannot pay this on a soldier's wages.

12:23.143 --> 12:26.113
[Maggie]
I wish I had the funds to help you,

12:26.146 --> 12:27.948
but I have no money of my own.

12:27.981 --> 12:30.083
I am at the mercy of the Tudors.

12:30.117 --> 12:33.386
[gentle music]

12:33.420 --> 12:35.455
[indistinct chatter]

12:35.489 --> 12:38.492
♪ ♪

12:46.166 --> 12:48.168
Lina's boys have grown so much.

12:48.201 --> 12:51.138
-Barnaby has learned--
-Barnaby.

12:51.171 --> 12:53.106
Such an English name.

12:54.074 --> 12:55.909
Lina would love to see you.

12:55.942 --> 12:57.377
[distant bell tolls]

12:57.410 --> 12:58.845
Catherine, is it true?

12:58.879 --> 13:00.847
Am I to marry the King of France now?

13:00.881 --> 13:02.249
[Catherine]
This is a scheme of Wolsey's.

13:02.282 --> 13:03.550
What has it to do with him?

13:03.783 --> 13:06.953
-France is our enemy.
-The king will see no merit in it.

13:06.987 --> 13:08.421
Listen to me.

13:08.455 --> 13:11.358
Charles is heir to Spain
and to the Holy Roman Empire.

13:11.391 --> 13:14.327
Your marriage will make you
the most powerful ally for England.

13:15.829 --> 13:17.097
Trust your brother.

13:19.366 --> 13:21.501
He is an excellent politician.

13:26.039 --> 13:27.474
Thank you, Catherine.

13:34.548 --> 13:37.250
Wolsey is a good politician, too.

13:37.284 --> 13:39.186
I am better.

13:39.219 --> 13:42.189
[dramatic music]

13:42.222 --> 13:45.859
Your Grace, the priest is a poisonous weed

13:45.892 --> 13:48.228
that twists about our throats.

13:48.261 --> 13:52.199
The council feels that his influence
upon the king has grown too great.

13:52.232 --> 13:55.869
Rest assured, Lord Stafford,
we will make no alliance with the French

13:55.902 --> 13:57.837
based on the advice
of an ambitious chaplain.

13:57.871 --> 14:00.874
♪ ♪

14:09.549 --> 14:11.218
[Catherine]
Chaplain Wolsey.

14:11.251 --> 14:12.919
Your Grace.

14:12.953 --> 14:14.854
Will you delight us today
with more schemes

14:14.888 --> 14:17.290
to ally England to her enemies?

14:17.324 --> 14:21.161
[laughter]

14:21.194 --> 14:22.229
Wolsey is right.

14:22.262 --> 14:26.900
I have decided to dissolve
my sister's betrothal to Charles

14:26.933 --> 14:29.135
and give her hand to Louis XII of France.

14:29.169 --> 14:30.403
What?

14:32.038 --> 14:34.507
Your Grace, may I venture to ask

14:34.541 --> 14:37.177
how such an alliance benefits England?

14:37.210 --> 14:38.345
[Henry]
No, you may not!

14:38.378 --> 14:40.146
You see, that's the problem
with all of you.

14:40.180 --> 14:43.950
You do not understand what benefits
the working people of England.

14:44.985 --> 14:46.253
This is my decision...

14:48.021 --> 14:49.589
...and it is God's will.

14:49.623 --> 14:52.626
♪ ♪

14:54.494 --> 14:55.962
Of course, Your Grace.

14:57.197 --> 14:59.032
An excellent--

14:59.065 --> 15:01.468
Henry, make no mistake.

15:04.104 --> 15:06.973
Wolsey's counsel is against me,
and you are allowing it.

15:08.008 --> 15:09.542
You are letting him humiliate me and--

15:09.576 --> 15:12.145
-It is not personal to you!
-Yes, it's personal!

15:18.585 --> 15:20.487
I went to war for this.

15:21.488 --> 15:24.491
I lost a child to stop the Scots
laying waste to England.

15:26.326 --> 15:28.328
We have been
in this fight together, Henry.

15:29.195 --> 15:31.631
Do not throw it in my face
and make my sacrifice for nothing.

15:31.665 --> 15:34.000
So you admit it?

15:34.034 --> 15:36.469
You lost the child
because you tried to be a man.

15:37.337 --> 15:39.572
I was a woman...

15:39.606 --> 15:42.375
fighting to protect our people.

15:42.409 --> 15:45.412
[somber music]

15:45.445 --> 15:48.448
♪ ♪

15:55.355 --> 15:57.290
[Catherine]
<i>Father, the alliance</i>

15:57.324 --> 16:00.093
<i>between Spain and England is now dead.</i>

16:01.561 --> 16:04.597
<i>Charles and Princess Mary will not marry.</i>

16:04.631 --> 16:07.200
<i>And it is all your doing.</i>

16:07.233 --> 16:10.236
[dramatic music]

16:10.270 --> 16:13.273
♪ ♪

16:17.510 --> 16:20.080
King Louis has agreed
to the match with Mary.

16:20.113 --> 16:22.449
We must find a French proxy

16:22.482 --> 16:25.151
so the betrothal service
can be held at once.

16:25.185 --> 16:28.121
We still have our prisoner
from the Battle of the Spurs.

16:29.122 --> 16:30.690
[Henry]
Excellent, Wolsey.

16:33.226 --> 16:35.462
[Wiltshire]
I'll have him made ready, Your Grace.

16:35.495 --> 16:37.397
[Henry]
Thank you, Thomas.

16:37.430 --> 16:40.567
[Catherine] <i>I hope you are satisfied</i>
<i>with your work...</i>

16:40.600 --> 16:44.270
<i>because it doesn't just hurt Spain.</i>

16:44.304 --> 16:46.539
<i>It hurts me, too,</i>

16:46.573 --> 16:48.708
<i>and my place at the English court.</i>

16:48.742 --> 16:51.378
♪ ♪

16:51.411 --> 16:53.079
His mind is set, Mary.

16:54.381 --> 16:56.516
We must make the best of it.

16:56.549 --> 16:59.519
♪ ♪

16:59.552 --> 17:03.256
Mary has a Spanish prince
or else a rich French king.

17:03.289 --> 17:04.457
She's so lucky.

17:04.491 --> 17:07.727
She is not lucky, Ursula,
for she has no say in it.

17:07.761 --> 17:10.363
The King of France is very old

17:10.397 --> 17:11.664
and French.

17:11.698 --> 17:13.032
I would have him.

17:13.733 --> 17:16.403
Ursula, marriage should be

17:16.436 --> 17:19.739
to someone you respect and find appealing.

17:19.773 --> 17:23.243
I choose whomever the king suggests--

17:23.276 --> 17:25.812
a man with power
and high standing in the court.

17:26.045 --> 17:28.281
A good match is not just
about high standing.

17:28.314 --> 17:30.250
It is, and that is what I want.

17:30.283 --> 17:32.085
I do not want to end up like you.

17:36.089 --> 17:37.524
Sorry.

17:37.557 --> 17:41.294
You are good, but we were starving

17:41.327 --> 17:43.830
and in danger for so many years.

17:45.298 --> 17:47.434
I want to know I will be safe.

17:47.467 --> 17:49.269
Riches do not keep you safe.

17:49.302 --> 17:51.771
They do. They will.

17:51.805 --> 17:53.807
And when the king names
a man for me to marry,

17:53.840 --> 17:55.408
I will take him.

17:55.442 --> 17:58.077
[birds chirping]

17:58.111 --> 17:59.412
[gasps softly]

18:03.683 --> 18:05.285
[More]
You are progressing very quickly.

18:05.318 --> 18:07.787
What did you learn today, Reggie?

18:09.322 --> 18:11.324
Oh, we have been discussing
Plato's theories

18:11.357 --> 18:13.493
of an egalitarian city-state.

18:14.627 --> 18:17.330
He is making great progress, Lady Pole.

18:18.298 --> 18:19.332
Thank you.

18:21.301 --> 18:22.302
Come.

18:23.169 --> 18:25.605
We promised we'd visit Lina
and the babies.

18:27.173 --> 18:29.843
[bells tolling]

18:32.579 --> 18:35.181
[doors open]

18:45.391 --> 18:50.263
On behalf of King Louis XII,
monarch of the House of Valois,

18:50.296 --> 18:53.666
will you take Princess Mary
to be your wife?

18:53.700 --> 18:55.468
Yes.

18:55.502 --> 18:57.504
Will you, Princess Mary,

18:57.537 --> 18:58.705
-take King Louis--
-No.

18:59.839 --> 19:03.142
[soft murmuring]

19:03.176 --> 19:05.678
Will you, Princess Mary--

19:05.712 --> 19:07.747
-No.
-[scattered gasps, murmuring]

19:07.780 --> 19:09.382
[Brandon]
Gutsy, horse.

19:09.415 --> 19:12.385
[dramatic music]

19:12.418 --> 19:15.421
♪ ♪

19:23.563 --> 19:25.665
[object slams on table]

19:25.698 --> 19:28.368
[Henry]
You tell my sister to oppose me,

19:28.401 --> 19:30.637
and you don't think this
the act of a traitor?

19:30.670 --> 19:32.772
-I-I did not tell her to do this.
-Don't deny it.

19:32.805 --> 19:34.874
This reeks of your interference.

19:34.908 --> 19:38.211
I promise you. It was not my doing.

19:38.244 --> 19:41.881
You are the only one in the court
who would dare to defy me.

19:41.915 --> 19:44.884
It is no secret
I do not like this match for Mary,

19:44.918 --> 19:46.486
but I bow to your will.

19:46.519 --> 19:48.555
But you don't.

19:48.588 --> 19:50.823
You don't give me what I need.

19:50.857 --> 19:52.792
I try, Henry!

19:52.825 --> 19:54.227
We want--

19:54.260 --> 19:56.696
[sighs]
We need the same thing.

19:56.729 --> 19:58.565
[Henry]
Then why is it so difficult?

19:58.598 --> 20:00.700
I am king!

20:00.733 --> 20:02.936
And God is at my side!

20:04.237 --> 20:06.973
How is it that I have no sons?

20:08.741 --> 20:10.577
I will bear you an heir.

20:12.412 --> 20:13.613
I promise you.

20:13.646 --> 20:16.616
[tense music]

20:16.649 --> 20:19.919
♪ ♪

20:19.953 --> 20:23.423
Tell my sister that she's building
a great pyre beneath her.

20:24.757 --> 20:27.560
And I will not hesitate to throw a torch.

20:27.594 --> 20:30.597
♪ ♪

20:39.472 --> 20:43.543
I have a letter for you from Lina.

20:43.576 --> 20:45.812
She wants to show her boys to you.

20:47.547 --> 20:49.782
I saw them.

20:49.816 --> 20:51.818
They are ordinary children.

20:56.756 --> 20:58.625
Your Grace,

20:58.658 --> 21:01.794
my daughter wishes to marry.

21:01.828 --> 21:05.465
She would be wed for politics and status.

21:05.498 --> 21:07.033
Then she is wise.

21:07.266 --> 21:10.370
Perhaps you could entreat
the king on my behalf

21:10.403 --> 21:12.772
to suggest a viable match for her.

21:12.805 --> 21:16.342
You should first ask the king
to return your lands and money

21:16.376 --> 21:19.012
so Ursula is an eligible proposition.

21:20.513 --> 21:22.715
-I will do that.
-[Catherine] But you should wait.

21:22.749 --> 21:26.386
The king is in a foul temper with us all.

21:28.287 --> 21:29.622
Especially me.

21:30.523 --> 21:32.058
Thank you.

21:32.291 --> 21:35.294
♪ ♪

21:35.328 --> 21:37.063
[footsteps departing]

21:37.296 --> 21:38.665
[sighs]

21:38.698 --> 21:40.667
[door closes]

21:40.700 --> 21:43.703
♪ ♪

21:52.645 --> 21:55.581
[bird screeches]

21:55.615 --> 21:58.017
[Meg]
<i>Dearest sister Catherine,</i>

21:58.051 --> 22:02.689
<i>you are a queen who inspires loyalty</i>
<i>in your people.</i>

22:02.722 --> 22:06.025
<i>How can I make my own people accept me?</i>

22:06.059 --> 22:08.027
<i>Help me, Catherine.</i>

22:08.061 --> 22:10.063
[child crying]

22:10.096 --> 22:14.000
<i>From your sister Margaret,</i>
<i>Queen of Scotland.</i>

22:14.033 --> 22:17.003
♪ ♪

22:23.676 --> 22:25.078
My queen.

22:26.713 --> 22:27.914
Forgive me.

22:29.082 --> 22:31.417
There-there is nothing to forgive.

22:32.085 --> 22:34.654
I am so sorry for your loss.

22:34.687 --> 22:37.590
Your father was kind.

22:38.591 --> 22:42.695
My son was fascinated with his beard.

22:47.467 --> 22:49.535
It was a fine beard.

22:49.569 --> 22:50.770
It was.

22:57.944 --> 23:00.113
Have you had any more dreams?

23:03.683 --> 23:06.452
I'm afraid to go to sleep in case I do.

23:07.620 --> 23:09.789
I don't want to know who dies next.

23:10.957 --> 23:13.626
[Angus] In my dreams,
I'm still on the battlefield.

23:17.630 --> 23:20.566
I'd not killed a man before Flodden.

23:22.668 --> 23:27.140
I came home with his blood
on my face like some hero.

23:29.809 --> 23:32.011
I keep waking up with the smell of it.

23:34.881 --> 23:37.683
[sniffles]

23:37.717 --> 23:40.787
There is nothing more inglorious

23:40.820 --> 23:43.556
than that glory that is gained by war.

23:45.992 --> 23:47.660
Is that Thomas More?

23:48.661 --> 23:50.429
You know his work?

23:50.463 --> 23:52.198
Of course.

23:52.431 --> 23:55.668
He is in the English court
and a favorite of my brother's.

23:57.069 --> 23:59.972
Everything good comes out of England.

24:00.006 --> 24:02.975
[soft music]

24:03.009 --> 24:05.912
Love rules without rules.

24:05.945 --> 24:08.981
That's my favorite line of his.

24:09.015 --> 24:11.651
Love rules without rules.

24:11.684 --> 24:14.687
♪ ♪

24:15.855 --> 24:17.690
I should leave you to your prayer.

24:19.692 --> 24:22.662
My prayer is always the same.

24:22.695 --> 24:25.698
♪ ♪

24:25.731 --> 24:28.201
Show me how to help my people.

24:29.702 --> 24:31.871
I struggle to hear the answer.

24:33.039 --> 24:34.207
If I may...

24:36.209 --> 24:40.479
I have found comfort
in giving bread to the poor.

24:40.513 --> 24:42.014
To see their simple smiles

24:42.048 --> 24:46.252
and to give them respite from hunger

24:46.485 --> 24:48.688
is enough to silence my own demons.

24:50.256 --> 24:52.091
For a moment at least.

24:52.124 --> 24:55.127
♪ ♪

24:59.098 --> 25:02.568
<i>[Lina singing in Spanish]</i>

25:02.602 --> 25:04.570
[baby cries]

25:04.604 --> 25:07.273
♪ ♪

25:07.506 --> 25:10.276
[babies crying]

25:10.509 --> 25:13.512
♪ ♪

25:16.515 --> 25:19.118
[knocking at door]

25:19.151 --> 25:22.154
[crying continues]

25:31.297 --> 25:32.531
[Lina]
Lady Pole.

25:33.633 --> 25:36.569
Catherine asked me
to bring two wet nurses,

25:36.602 --> 25:38.104
one for each child.

25:38.938 --> 25:40.640
Catherine will not come?

25:40.673 --> 25:42.108
It is hard for her, Lina.

25:43.609 --> 25:46.145
You have the things she wants most.

25:46.178 --> 25:48.247
But this is her gift to you.

25:48.281 --> 25:50.950
[gentle music]

25:50.983 --> 25:53.819
♪ ♪

26:04.730 --> 26:07.066
You have a great appetite
this evening, Henry.

26:07.099 --> 26:09.168
Hmm, I was hawking with Stafford.

26:09.201 --> 26:11.771
I could think of no more affairs of state.

26:11.804 --> 26:12.905
I had to get out.

26:12.939 --> 26:14.974
I would like to come with you.

26:18.644 --> 26:19.979
[doors creak closed]

26:20.012 --> 26:22.648
-Chaplain Wolsey.
-Forgive my lateness.

26:22.682 --> 26:25.651
I was christening the new child

26:25.685 --> 26:28.587
of one of your loyal subjects.

26:33.993 --> 26:35.895
You did not feel called
to become a butcher

26:35.928 --> 26:37.663
like your father, Wolsey?

26:37.697 --> 26:39.932
My calling is to serve God.

26:39.966 --> 26:43.336
Providing meat to hungry people
also serves God, surely.

26:43.369 --> 26:45.705
God wills me to His service.

26:45.738 --> 26:48.207
And to offer His counsel to the king.

26:48.240 --> 26:51.844
Tell me, Wolsey,
what is God's will for me?

26:53.012 --> 26:54.680
Does He love me?

26:54.714 --> 26:58.117
God challenges His kings
because He loves them

26:58.150 --> 27:01.087
the way a father loves his son...

27:01.120 --> 27:04.991
the way you would love
your own son if you had one.

27:05.024 --> 27:06.092
[Catherine]
When.

27:06.125 --> 27:08.928
It is not a question of if, chaplain.

27:08.961 --> 27:11.697
[Wolsey] God tests our faith
at times, but, Your Grace...

27:12.698 --> 27:15.401
...He finds no fault with you.

27:18.337 --> 27:20.339
And my sister Mary?

27:20.373 --> 27:22.708
Does He find fault with her?

27:22.742 --> 27:24.677
I will pray for her.

27:24.710 --> 27:28.881
That she finds the humility
to follow God's will.

27:28.914 --> 27:30.683
[Henry]
Thank you, Wolsey.

27:30.716 --> 27:33.853
Your counsel gives me much comfort.

27:33.886 --> 27:34.920
It will be rewarded.

27:36.222 --> 27:38.891
I shall appoint you Archbishop of York.

27:43.396 --> 27:45.231
[Wolsey]
Thank you, Your Grace.

27:46.198 --> 27:48.067
And thank you, chaplain...

27:49.268 --> 27:51.404
...for the comfort you give my husband.

27:52.405 --> 27:54.173
I will pray for you also,

27:54.206 --> 27:56.142
for I know you would also do well

27:56.175 --> 27:58.711
to find the humility to follow God's will.

27:59.845 --> 28:01.313
[Wolsey]
Your Grace.

28:01.347 --> 28:04.316
[dramatic music]

28:04.350 --> 28:07.386
♪ ♪

28:07.420 --> 28:10.089
[Mary]
He can't make me.

28:10.122 --> 28:12.758
[Catherine] Everything you have
is at his pleasure, Mary.

28:13.926 --> 28:16.395
If he will not bend, then you must.

28:16.429 --> 28:18.397
We must do his bidding.

28:18.431 --> 28:21.801
My whole life I have been taught
to despise the French.

28:21.834 --> 28:24.003
I know their duplicity and cruelty.

28:24.036 --> 28:27.006
Before I came to England,
I was told that the English never washed.

28:27.039 --> 28:29.442
It is a little true. I hate bathing.

28:29.475 --> 28:32.878
I was also told the English
had no fighting spirit.

28:32.912 --> 28:36.749
That they were corpulent and crass
and didn't educate their women.

28:36.782 --> 28:38.784
But I have found my family here.

28:40.419 --> 28:43.422
If there is another war,
we will be enemies.

28:44.457 --> 28:46.959
What if you were to have
your own choice next time, Mary?

28:48.194 --> 28:51.063
What if the king agreed
that if Louis were to die,

28:51.097 --> 28:53.399
then you could choose
your next husband for yourself?

28:53.432 --> 28:55.334
That still means I must wed him.

28:55.367 --> 28:57.136
Louis is old and fat.

28:58.137 --> 29:00.039
Precisely.

29:00.072 --> 29:02.174
He is old...

29:02.208 --> 29:03.776
and fat.

29:03.809 --> 29:06.812
♪ ♪

29:07.913 --> 29:10.916
[both grunting]

29:15.054 --> 29:17.022
[Henry]
You're slow today, Charlie.

29:17.056 --> 29:18.324
[Catherine]
My king.

29:19.291 --> 29:20.993
I have good news.

29:21.026 --> 29:23.496
[swords clattering]

29:23.529 --> 29:24.964
Well?

29:24.997 --> 29:26.832
Your sister Mary will do as you ask.

29:26.866 --> 29:28.767
She is willing to renounce her betrothal

29:28.801 --> 29:32.071
to Duke Charles of Burgundy
and marry King Louis.

29:33.806 --> 29:36.342
-She has only one small condition.
-No conditions.

29:36.375 --> 29:38.978
Should Louis die,
then she would have the liberty

29:39.011 --> 29:40.779
to choose her next husband for herself.

29:40.813 --> 29:43.516
Otherwise you will have months
of argument,

29:43.549 --> 29:47.052
and perhaps Louis will grow tired
of waiting and take a different wife.

29:48.521 --> 29:50.823
And your French alliance would be lost.

29:50.856 --> 29:51.857
Very well.

29:54.894 --> 29:56.562
It is good news, isn't it, Henry?

29:56.795 --> 30:00.533
No, the only good news would be a son.

30:02.835 --> 30:05.504
[grunting]

30:05.538 --> 30:07.106
[swords clatter]

30:08.207 --> 30:11.177
[somber choral music]

30:11.210 --> 30:14.213
♪ ♪

30:15.414 --> 30:18.317
[Catherine]
<i>My sister Meg.</i>

30:18.350 --> 30:22.221
<i>In London, Wolsey goes</i>
<i>from strength to strength.</i>

30:22.254 --> 30:24.990
<i>He is beatified in your brother's eyes</i>

30:25.024 --> 30:27.893
<i>and has been made Archbishop of York.</i>

30:29.028 --> 30:32.198
<i>He fails to hold</i>
<i>the English court in thrall,</i>

30:32.231 --> 30:34.366
<i>but he has the king's love.</i>

30:34.400 --> 30:36.902
♪ ♪

30:36.936 --> 30:41.240
<i>Honor is heaped upon him</i>
<i>while I fall from my husband's grace.</i>

30:43.509 --> 30:47.046
<i>I have little to say</i>
<i>in this moment of my life...</i>

30:47.079 --> 30:49.882
<i>about how to win loyalty.</i>

30:49.915 --> 30:52.551
<i>I am at war myself...</i>

30:52.585 --> 30:55.020
<i>trying to stay in the world,</i>

30:55.054 --> 30:57.923
<i>endlessly fighting this grief.</i>

30:59.091 --> 31:01.894
<i>I lost the child whom I was carrying</i>

31:01.927 --> 31:04.430
<i>when we last stood face-to-face.</i>

31:04.463 --> 31:06.632
<i>Perhaps you have heard.</i>

31:06.865 --> 31:08.100
You sent for me?

31:09.435 --> 31:12.104
I want you to show me what it is like.

31:13.339 --> 31:15.407
Take me to my people, Angus.

31:15.441 --> 31:17.443
Let us do charity together.

31:18.944 --> 31:21.280
[Catherine]
<i>I know one day I will return from this.</i>

31:22.915 --> 31:26.418
<i>In the meantime,</i>
<i>I must play at being a queen.</i>

31:26.452 --> 31:29.088
<i>I must play at living an enviable life.</i>

31:30.456 --> 31:32.458
<i>I must pretend at strength.</i>

31:34.293 --> 31:38.931
<i>I must be someone who can be admired,</i>
<i>when in truth I feel nothing but shame.</i>

31:41.100 --> 31:43.435
<i>I must be seen to be pious...</i>

31:43.469 --> 31:46.438
♪ ♪

31:46.472 --> 31:47.973
<i>...a good Christian...</i>

31:49.141 --> 31:51.143
<i>...and a good wife,</i>

31:51.176 --> 31:53.279
<i>but I do not feel good.</i>

31:53.312 --> 31:56.282
♪ ♪

31:56.315 --> 31:58.517
Allow your queen to pass.

31:58.550 --> 32:01.553
♪ ♪

32:01.587 --> 32:04.490
[indistinct chatter, children crying]

32:06.125 --> 32:09.161
[Catherine]
<i>There are times when I want to scream.</i>

32:10.162 --> 32:13.165
<i>But I know that if I did,</i>
<i>I would never stop.</i>

32:14.133 --> 32:17.002
<i>I would rage against God,</i>

32:17.036 --> 32:18.671
<i>against my own body...</i>

32:20.506 --> 32:22.975
<i>...and against my own helplessness.</i>

32:23.008 --> 32:25.978
[child crying]

32:26.011 --> 32:29.014
♪ ♪

32:33.352 --> 32:36.021
<i>Life does not feel worth living to me.</i>

32:37.022 --> 32:39.525
<i>I know what love and pleasure look like...</i>

32:41.226 --> 32:43.128
<i>...but I cannot remember how they feel.</i>

32:44.430 --> 32:46.598
<i>If I let myself cry,</i>

32:46.632 --> 32:49.535
<i>I am afraid it will tear me to pieces.</i>

32:51.203 --> 32:53.372
<i>It would be such a joy to feel.</i>

32:54.540 --> 32:57.543
<i>Then at least I would know</i>
<i>I am still alive.</i>

32:59.211 --> 33:02.081
[distant horse neighs]

33:02.114 --> 33:05.150
[distant dog barking]

33:05.184 --> 33:08.153
♪ ♪

33:08.187 --> 33:12.024
[men shouting and grunting]

33:12.057 --> 33:15.027
♪ ♪

33:15.060 --> 33:18.030
[indistinct shouting]

33:18.063 --> 33:21.700
<i>♪ Oh, bury me 'neath the bracken bush ♪</i>

33:21.734 --> 33:25.104
<i>♪ That grows near yonder breer ♪</i>

33:25.137 --> 33:28.540
<i>♪ Let never a living mortal ken ♪</i>

33:28.574 --> 33:32.277
<i>♪ That Douglas he lies here ♪</i>

33:32.311 --> 33:36.482
<i>♪ They've lifted up that noble lord ♪</i>

33:36.515 --> 33:41.253
<i>♪ A salt tear in their e'e ♪</i>

33:41.286 --> 33:45.190
I hereby renounce my betrothal
to Charles of Burgundy.

33:45.224 --> 33:49.261
I choose instead to marry
King Louis XII of France.

33:49.294 --> 33:51.764
I do so of my own volition

33:51.797 --> 33:56.101
and am in all things ever ready
to obey the king's good pleasure.

33:57.703 --> 33:58.771
[Henry]
Thomas.

34:00.372 --> 34:03.108
Perhaps your daughters
might attend my sister as her ladies,

34:03.142 --> 34:04.743
as we journey to France for the wedding.

34:04.777 --> 34:09.214
Mary, Anne, the king honors us all.

34:11.417 --> 34:14.553
For once we may travel
without fear of invasion.

34:14.586 --> 34:16.321
[Henry]
Well, my own sister Meg

34:16.355 --> 34:18.690
rules the enemy on our doorstep.

34:18.724 --> 34:21.560
But Stafford will mind England
in my absence.

34:23.529 --> 34:27.132
Just keep my throne
warm for me, old friend.

34:30.135 --> 34:31.403
[Brandon]
Horse.

34:33.739 --> 34:36.608
Are you coming to France
to see me wed, Charlie?

34:36.642 --> 34:40.546
I have responsibilities
I must attend to here.

34:41.513 --> 34:43.549
What responsibilities?

34:43.582 --> 34:47.219
I am to be betrothed
to my ward, Elizabeth.

34:47.252 --> 34:49.288
She is only eight years old!

34:49.321 --> 34:51.223
We will not wed until she's of age.

34:51.256 --> 34:53.625
But she brings the title Viscount Lisle,

34:53.659 --> 34:56.662
and the king would have me take it, so...

34:56.695 --> 34:58.397
Oh, Charlie,

34:58.430 --> 35:01.300
the ladies of the court
will all be devastated.

35:01.333 --> 35:02.334
[laughs]

35:02.367 --> 35:04.570
Thank you for your sympathy, horse.

35:04.603 --> 35:07.706
So we are both
to marry people of the wrong age.

35:07.739 --> 35:10.509
[both chuckle]

35:14.112 --> 35:15.848
Then I must say good-bye to you here.

35:18.484 --> 35:21.186
[gentle string music]

35:21.220 --> 35:22.354
Go well.

35:23.655 --> 35:25.491
You too, Charlie.

35:25.524 --> 35:28.527
♪ ♪

35:31.697 --> 35:33.832
My Queen, the crowds were growing outside.

35:33.866 --> 35:35.601
We had to let them through.

35:35.634 --> 35:36.668
I will talk to them.

35:36.702 --> 35:38.403
[Gavin]
It's too late for talk.

35:38.437 --> 35:40.339
They're about to riot.

35:40.372 --> 35:42.841
[dramatic music]

35:42.875 --> 35:44.443
You look after the children.

35:44.476 --> 35:47.446
[crowd shouting outside]

35:47.479 --> 35:49.715
♪ ♪

35:49.748 --> 35:51.683
[all]

35:51.717 --> 35:53.685
Where is our king?

35:53.719 --> 35:57.523
Where is our king? Where is our king?

36:00.259 --> 36:02.628
Where is our king?

36:02.661 --> 36:06.198
Scotland is not a headless state!

36:07.232 --> 36:09.401
I am head of state.

36:10.402 --> 36:13.372
-I know you are angry.
-[man] Where's our king?

36:13.405 --> 36:15.407
[Meg]
I am angry, too.

36:16.275 --> 36:18.744
You are grieving for your king.

36:19.912 --> 36:21.813
So am I.

36:21.847 --> 36:23.949
You are grieving for your sons...

36:25.250 --> 36:26.885
...and husbands.

36:26.919 --> 36:28.921
We have all lost our own.

36:29.922 --> 36:33.559
You, clan leaders
who have come to Edinburgh,

36:33.592 --> 36:35.961
go home to your communities.

36:36.194 --> 36:37.663
Lead your people.

36:37.696 --> 36:39.898
Organize a great feast

36:39.932 --> 36:43.335
in remembrance
of those who did not return.

36:44.803 --> 36:46.572
Gather together.

36:46.605 --> 36:49.408
Do not walk alone. 'Tis--

36:50.776 --> 36:54.880
It is too much grief
for a single heart to bear.

36:56.715 --> 37:01.520
Teach your sons and daughters
to cry if they need to cry.

37:02.621 --> 37:04.656
Not hidden behind closed doors...

37:05.791 --> 37:08.427
...with their heads held high.

37:08.460 --> 37:11.797
We are not ashamed of our grief.

37:12.898 --> 37:15.500
We loved our children,

37:15.534 --> 37:18.637
our fathers, our sons, and our friends.

37:19.805 --> 37:22.741
We loved our king,

37:22.774 --> 37:25.811
and that is why now we grieve.

37:27.479 --> 37:29.381
[exhales sharply]

37:33.619 --> 37:38.590
<i>♪ Oh, bury me 'neath the bracken bush ♪</i>

37:38.624 --> 37:42.928
<i>♪ That lies by yonder breer ♪</i>

37:42.961 --> 37:46.798
<i>♪ Let never a living mortal ken ♪</i>

37:46.832 --> 37:50.335
<i>♪ That Douglas he lies here ♪</i>

37:50.369 --> 37:54.906
<i>♪ They've lifted up that noble lord ♪</i>

37:54.940 --> 37:58.577
<i>♪ With a salt tear in their e'e ♪</i>

37:58.610 --> 38:02.280
<i>♪ They've buried him</i>
<i>'Neath the bracken bush ♪</i>

38:02.314 --> 38:06.785
<i>♪ That his merry men might not see ♪</i>

38:06.818 --> 38:09.955
[bird cawing]

38:09.988 --> 38:12.958
[all cheering]

38:12.991 --> 38:15.994
[cheerful music]

38:16.028 --> 38:19.031
♪ ♪

38:33.779 --> 38:37.015
I hate the sea. I hate it.

38:37.049 --> 38:40.919
[ship groaning]

38:43.555 --> 38:45.724
Are you quite well, Archbishop?

38:48.727 --> 38:52.698
[vomiting]

38:52.731 --> 38:54.700
[Catherine chuckles]

38:54.733 --> 38:57.703
[dramatic music]

38:57.736 --> 39:00.739
♪ ♪

39:10.749 --> 39:13.385
Princess Mary looks terrified.

39:13.418 --> 39:15.487
[chuckles]
She should be,

39:15.520 --> 39:17.589
when marriage is a political game.

39:18.590 --> 39:21.593
What do you think marriage
should be, Lady Pole?

39:22.894 --> 39:26.398
I believe marriage can be a true union.

39:27.766 --> 39:29.468
You are romantic.

39:29.501 --> 39:30.736
[Maggie scoffs]

39:30.769 --> 39:33.004
All creatures crave union.

39:33.038 --> 39:35.407
There's nothing fanciful about it.

39:35.440 --> 39:38.043
It is more natural than
the machinations of court.

39:39.878 --> 39:43.081
I was lucky with my husband.

39:43.115 --> 39:46.918
My marriage to Richard
was arranged, but...

39:46.952 --> 39:48.487
it was love.

39:51.957 --> 39:55.093
Alice, um, who you met,

39:55.127 --> 39:56.628
she's my second wife.

39:57.696 --> 39:59.731
She's a very good mother
to mine and Jane's children,

39:59.765 --> 40:02.134
and I am very grateful to her for that,
but, um...

40:03.135 --> 40:04.870
...marriage is not to her taste.

40:06.004 --> 40:08.140
She favors a cold bed.

40:15.180 --> 40:18.450
Do you believe that true union

40:18.483 --> 40:20.819
is possible more than once in a lifetime?

40:23.488 --> 40:24.489
I do.

40:28.560 --> 40:32.998
Yes, perhaps when one has given up
all hope of love...

40:34.699 --> 40:39.437
...one meets a friend who seems
to share one's own soul...

40:41.173 --> 40:44.476
...and whose beauty and grace make a folly

40:44.509 --> 40:46.978
of all but the truest union.

40:47.012 --> 40:50.015
♪ ♪

41:16.908 --> 41:19.211
[Mary]
He is 500 years of age.

41:20.212 --> 41:22.247
[Catherine]
You have steel, Mary.

41:22.480 --> 41:24.182
You are strong enough for this.

41:24.216 --> 41:27.219
♪ ♪

41:42.567 --> 41:45.704
I present Princess Mary of England.

41:45.737 --> 41:49.040
May your marriage yield a union
that is peaceful and powerful

41:49.074 --> 41:51.076
between our two great nations.

41:57.148 --> 42:02.153
[in French] Princess, your portrait
did you an injustice.

42:02.754 --> 42:07.259
The shine of your hair
is like the back of a raven.

42:09.261 --> 42:12.230
[gentle music]

42:12.264 --> 42:14.933
♪ ♪

42:31.750 --> 42:33.718
[in English]
[Henry] Congratulations on your marriage.

42:38.957 --> 42:40.792
[Catherine]
Mary, you look beautiful.

42:42.961 --> 42:45.997
[Henry]
Albany! A Scot in France!

42:46.031 --> 42:48.199
Well, you were ever in each other's beds.

42:48.233 --> 42:50.135
[laughs]

42:50.168 --> 42:53.972
Would you rather I was back in Edinburgh,
taking the regency from your sister?

42:54.005 --> 42:56.775
I have the right if I should choose it.

42:56.808 --> 42:58.977
I am next in line.

43:05.150 --> 43:07.786
When I dreamed of conquering France
and winning peace for England,

43:07.819 --> 43:09.587
the dreams were always full of blood.

43:09.621 --> 43:12.324
I never imagined
there'd be wine and music.

43:12.357 --> 43:14.359
[More chuckles]

43:16.161 --> 43:18.997
[Maggie]
Your Grace, may I--

43:20.732 --> 43:23.234
I wish to ask...

43:23.268 --> 43:26.838
would you return my land and titles to me?

43:26.871 --> 43:29.174
Forgive me. It is not for my sake.

43:30.308 --> 43:31.843
I'm sorry.

43:31.876 --> 43:33.945
The queen said it was not
the best time to ask.

43:33.979 --> 43:35.747
-I should have listened--
-Why is it not the best time?

43:36.748 --> 43:41.653
Because you are not
at your happiest, Your Grace.

43:41.686 --> 43:43.755
[chuckles]

43:43.788 --> 43:47.258
Aunt Maggie, it would give me pleasure
to return what my father took from you.

43:47.292 --> 43:49.694
Your earldom, Countess of Salisbury.

43:49.728 --> 43:51.629
And I'll afford you a modest income.

43:51.663 --> 43:52.731
[chuckles]

43:52.764 --> 43:54.032
-Thank you, Your Grace.
-Mm.

43:54.065 --> 43:55.066
I did not think--

43:55.100 --> 43:56.368
But it is time that you remarry.

43:57.869 --> 43:58.870
What?

44:00.038 --> 44:01.339
I am not ready.

44:01.373 --> 44:03.842
Well, I'd be more inclined
to give you back the earldom

44:03.875 --> 44:06.111
if I knew you were safe
from fortune hunters.

44:06.144 --> 44:08.246
But I do not wish to remarry.

44:08.279 --> 44:11.683
I only ask for my title
to ensure a good match for my daughter.

44:11.716 --> 44:13.385
She has asked for your suggestion.

44:16.054 --> 44:18.857
Young Henry Stafford.
He's set to inherit Buckinghamshire.

44:18.890 --> 44:20.058
He'll have her.

44:20.091 --> 44:21.292
[Wiltshire]
Perfect choice, Your Highness.

44:21.326 --> 44:22.660
Thank you, Your Grace.

44:22.694 --> 44:25.063
And might I suggest
William Compton for you?

44:27.065 --> 44:28.967
Your Groom of the Stool?

44:29.000 --> 44:30.001
-Hmm.
-[Maggie scoffs]

44:30.035 --> 44:32.704
I do not have any feelings
for Sir William.

44:32.737 --> 44:34.773
Well, he feels very warmly towards you.

44:34.806 --> 44:36.408
We spend a lot of time together.

44:36.441 --> 44:39.711
He never misses an opportunity
to speak your name.

44:39.744 --> 44:41.913
He's particularly taken
with how the color in your neck

44:41.946 --> 44:43.415
rises when you're embarrassed.

44:45.250 --> 44:47.085
I will think on it.

44:47.118 --> 44:49.921
Yes, think on it and agree.

44:51.823 --> 44:54.893
Thomas More tells me that your son Reggie

44:54.926 --> 44:57.162
displays a leaning for the priesthood.

44:57.195 --> 44:58.963
I'll support his education.

44:58.997 --> 45:00.698
He'll be sent away to Oxford.

45:04.836 --> 45:07.372
Oh, and enjoy the evening, Lady Aunt.

45:14.012 --> 45:15.447
Henry Stafford.

45:15.480 --> 45:19.417
-The king says Henry Stafford.
-I'll take him.

45:19.451 --> 45:23.154
[stammers]
See first if you feel well around him.

45:23.188 --> 45:26.124
There are certain feelings
required for a man and woman--

45:26.157 --> 45:29.461
I know about the shaking
of the sheets, Lady Mother.

45:29.494 --> 45:32.964
Princess Mary talks about it all the time.

45:32.997 --> 45:34.766
[whispering]
She is dreading it.

45:34.799 --> 45:37.969
-But you do not need to dread it.
-I don't.

45:38.002 --> 45:40.839
It will not play a part in my decisions.

45:40.872 --> 45:42.807
I will tell Henry Stafford
that I want him.

45:42.841 --> 45:44.876
[sighs softly]

45:44.909 --> 45:47.912
[string music playing]

45:47.946 --> 45:50.949
♪ ♪

45:55.987 --> 45:58.022
May I be the first
to offer my congratulations

45:58.056 --> 45:59.958
to the Countess of Salisbury.

46:00.825 --> 46:03.328
-I'm delighted for you.
-Thank you, Sir William.

46:03.361 --> 46:07.899
I'm most disarmed by the craftsmanship
on the paneling in the great hall.

46:07.932 --> 46:09.167
Countess...

46:10.335 --> 46:14.172
...would you do me the honor of looking
at each panel with me?

46:14.205 --> 46:15.874
Oh, uh...

46:15.907 --> 46:19.010
They really are endlessly distracting.

46:24.015 --> 46:25.984
Of course.

46:26.017 --> 46:30.021
[indistinct chatter]

46:30.054 --> 46:33.057
♪ ♪

46:36.794 --> 46:39.797
[chatter and music continue faintly]

46:45.870 --> 46:47.138
[Mary]
Your Grace.

46:47.172 --> 46:48.540
My king.

46:54.212 --> 46:57.515
Do you think we can recover
from this, Catherine?

46:59.417 --> 47:00.451
You and I?

47:02.053 --> 47:03.388
I want to.

47:04.455 --> 47:06.457
I want it to be as it was before.

47:07.225 --> 47:08.860
So do I.

47:11.095 --> 47:12.530
But it can't be, Henry.

47:14.065 --> 47:15.466
Why can't it?

47:15.500 --> 47:19.037
I stand here with a void
in the middle of my body.

47:20.338 --> 47:24.075
And you think God is punishing me,
but I have done nothing wrong.

47:26.911 --> 47:27.912
Come.

47:33.518 --> 47:35.520
[Henry] There is nothing wrong
in what I ask for.

47:36.955 --> 47:40.525
I need an heir so my throne is safe.

47:40.558 --> 47:42.393
I want this, too.

47:42.427 --> 47:44.395
Without a son, I'm weak.

47:44.429 --> 47:47.265
It-it's a sign that God does not bless me.

47:47.298 --> 47:49.567
It makes my enemies brave.

47:49.601 --> 47:52.070
I must live in fear of death
more than any man

47:52.103 --> 47:55.440
because-because that
would leave the throne empty.

47:55.473 --> 47:59.210
And my life is stopped
while we try to make another child,

47:59.244 --> 48:01.946
and it's-it's choking me.

48:01.980 --> 48:03.948
It chokes me, too, Henry.

48:06.217 --> 48:09.053
I don't want to make love to you

48:09.087 --> 48:11.089
because it's sad.

48:11.122 --> 48:12.190
It's just sad.

48:13.291 --> 48:16.027
It used to be my greatest joy on Earth.

48:19.530 --> 48:20.632
I know.

48:23.968 --> 48:25.970
Of all the battles...

48:26.971 --> 48:30.975
...everything I've seen,
his little body bundled up like--

48:31.009 --> 48:34.112
Don't you think I will give anything
to have our son alive?

48:34.145 --> 48:36.981
[dramatic music]

48:37.015 --> 48:38.316
I miss him.

48:39.684 --> 48:41.319
His kicking.

48:42.553 --> 48:45.089
And he had will Henry.

48:45.123 --> 48:46.491
I could feel it in me.

48:47.925 --> 48:50.328
I thought, "This boy
will be just like his father."

48:52.964 --> 48:54.365
I wanted to see him in your arms.

48:54.399 --> 48:56.234
Well, I wish you hadn't fought.

48:57.535 --> 49:02.440
I wish that you had been a wife
instead of a soldier.

49:02.473 --> 49:04.342
But then I'd be someone else.

49:06.010 --> 49:07.679
And you want me, Henry.

49:07.712 --> 49:10.048
I don't.

49:10.081 --> 49:11.382
Not now.

49:11.416 --> 49:13.251
Don't lie.

49:13.284 --> 49:15.353
You've always wanted me.

49:17.155 --> 49:19.557
And, Henry, I want you so badly.

49:19.590 --> 49:22.593
♪ ♪

49:25.363 --> 49:28.666
[Louis]
Oh, my sweet English girl

49:28.700 --> 49:32.337
sitting there all alone.

49:32.370 --> 49:33.671
My love.

49:33.705 --> 49:35.540
<i>Ma femme.</i>

49:40.411 --> 49:42.413
You are...

49:42.447 --> 49:45.550
a little afraid maybe?

49:47.285 --> 49:49.487
You are blessed.

49:50.621 --> 49:55.560
It is better to lie with an older man
the first time.

49:58.129 --> 50:01.366
I will try not to hurt you.

50:01.399 --> 50:03.768
[both moaning]

50:04.001 --> 50:06.771
[gentle orchestral music]

50:07.004 --> 50:10.007
♪ ♪

50:27.525 --> 50:28.526
[Louis]
Oh.

50:28.559 --> 50:31.562
[lively orchestral music]

50:31.596 --> 50:34.732
[laughter]

50:34.766 --> 50:37.769
♪ ♪

50:37.802 --> 50:40.705
[Louis]
Ooh! [laughs]

50:43.074 --> 50:45.042
Oh. Oh!

50:45.076 --> 50:47.478
[laughing]

50:47.512 --> 50:49.580
♪ ♪

50:49.614 --> 50:52.417
[breathing heavily]

50:52.450 --> 50:55.453
♪ ♪

50:59.624 --> 51:02.627
[gasps, snores]

51:22.213 --> 51:25.349
Everything has changed
since you stood before us.

51:25.383 --> 51:28.619
You healed everyone
with your sweet voice, my queen.

51:28.653 --> 51:31.189
I didn't think it was possible
to make a whole country cry.

51:31.856 --> 51:33.524
It's because of you.

51:33.558 --> 51:34.559
No.

51:36.761 --> 51:39.430
You...

51:39.464 --> 51:42.200
showed me the world outside.

51:42.233 --> 51:44.569
You are the greatest queen
Scotland's ever known.

51:46.370 --> 51:49.207
I mean, that's what people
are saying about you.

51:49.240 --> 51:50.675
Are they?

51:50.708 --> 51:53.144
They're saying how brave you are

51:53.177 --> 51:57.815
and how you don't favor
one clan over another and...

51:59.217 --> 52:00.518
Your eyes.

52:09.494 --> 52:12.363
Sorry. I don't know what came over me.

52:14.131 --> 52:15.700
I kissed you.

52:24.141 --> 52:26.277
[bird cawing]

52:26.310 --> 52:27.845
[Bessie]
I do believe Charlie Brandon

52:27.879 --> 52:30.314
is what God intended Adam to be.

52:30.348 --> 52:32.316
He's perfect in every way.

52:32.350 --> 52:35.186
I have seen him
without his shirt brandishing a sword.

52:35.219 --> 52:36.821
Be quiet, Bessie.

52:36.854 --> 52:38.389
If you love a man's body,

52:38.422 --> 52:40.892
it is not to share
with everyone you speak to.

52:47.231 --> 52:49.233
[horse chuffs]

52:53.704 --> 52:56.607
Your Grace, may I speak with you?

53:00.177 --> 53:02.480
Lina told me what you did at Flodden.

53:04.749 --> 53:06.717
I know you are brave.

53:06.751 --> 53:09.687
So I ask you humbly, Highness--

53:09.720 --> 53:12.256
I will go and see her and the children.

53:14.358 --> 53:17.728
[birds cawing]

53:17.762 --> 53:20.731
[gentle music]

53:20.765 --> 53:23.734
♪ ♪

53:23.768 --> 53:26.470
[door opens]

53:32.944 --> 53:34.211
[in Spanish]
Highness!

53:35.713 --> 53:37.448
I have missed you!

53:37.481 --> 53:39.750
[door closes]

53:39.784 --> 53:41.919
I have been waiting for you here.

53:43.287 --> 53:44.388
Have I done something wrong?

53:44.422 --> 53:46.591
[in English]
No, I-I--

53:46.624 --> 53:48.259
She's here now, Lina.

53:48.292 --> 53:50.928
Her Grace is here now.

53:50.962 --> 53:53.965
♪ ♪

54:00.738 --> 54:01.872
[chuckles]

54:04.308 --> 54:05.643
He's so fat.

54:05.676 --> 54:08.245
[both chuckle]

54:08.279 --> 54:09.947
Now he is.

54:09.981 --> 54:11.649
Thank you.

54:15.353 --> 54:16.921
Do you want to hold him?

54:19.023 --> 54:20.024
Come.

54:26.030 --> 54:27.798
[Catherine chuckles]

54:27.832 --> 54:29.600
[baby fusses]

54:29.634 --> 54:31.969
<i>Hola, mi cielito.</i>

54:32.003 --> 54:34.572
-[baby fusses]
-[chuckles]

54:38.676 --> 54:41.345
I am sorry I could not come before.

54:42.346 --> 54:43.514
I wanted to.

54:43.881 --> 54:48.019
[in Spanish] I am sorry for the loss
of your son, Highness.

54:48.052 --> 54:51.022
[gentle music]

54:51.055 --> 54:53.324
♪ ♪

54:53.357 --> 54:55.526
[in English]
Everything died for a while.

54:57.962 --> 55:00.297
Everything in me was so cold.

55:02.466 --> 55:04.635
And between me and Henry...

55:06.337 --> 55:07.872
Is it better now?

55:09.707 --> 55:10.708
Yes.

55:13.077 --> 55:15.513
I think we have found each other again.

55:15.546 --> 55:18.549
♪ ♪

55:52.883 --> 55:55.419
[Henry]
I betroth you to one another.

56:00.091 --> 56:02.093
We are strong, Archbishop.

56:03.527 --> 56:05.730
And none shall come between us.

56:05.763 --> 56:08.733
♪ ♪

56:16.140 --> 56:19.110
[dramatic singing in Spanish]

56:19.143 --> 56:22.146
♪ ♪
